WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.160
[Amit Varma]: All of us have heard stories of partition. Families torn apart, loved ones killed, women

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:14.960
[Amit Varma]: raped, lives destroyed, trains arriving in stations filled with dead bodies. Victims

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:19.800
[Amit Varma]: of slaughter not just of humans, but humanity. I've heard these stories all my life, but

00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:24.000
[Amit Varma]: they seem distant and far away, as if they were from an old novel, or even when they

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.720
[Amit Varma]: were real, as if they were from a black and white picture book and not really real. We

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:33.480
[Amit Varma]: all know that in our lives, we will face personal grief. People we love will die, and then we

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:38.480
[Amit Varma]: will die. But we have always assumed or at least hoped that as a nation, we would not

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:44.120
[Amit Varma]: encounter collective grief again. Well, here we are. This time the details are different.

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:49.180
[Amit Varma]: We don't yet know how many have died in India because of COVID-19 and how many will die.

00:00:49.180 --> 00:00:53.520
[Amit Varma]: What we do know is that the suffering this time is far more widespread than at any other

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:58.280
[Amit Varma]: time in our history. It has touched every corner of this country I love. Every morning

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:03.440
[Amit Varma]: these days, I spend half an hour after I wake up just writing condolence messages. I'm so

00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:09.160
[Amit Varma]: sorry for your loss. Take care, get better soon. In places like Delhi, every single friend

00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:13.680
[Amit Varma]: I have is affected. And I believe it is worse in our heartlands, where the hospitals cannot

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:18.960
[Amit Varma]: run out of oxygen, because there are no hospitals, where people get ill, and then they die. And

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:23.440
[Amit Varma]: there is no cause of death noted down, no accounting to be made. A few days ago, my

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:28.720
[Amit Varma]: father also died. The municipality didn't allow us near his body, understandably so,

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:33.320
[Amit Varma]: or inside the crematorium. We watched from a distance until one man came and pointed

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:37.840
[Amit Varma]: to the smoke coming from a distant tower. That was the last I saw of my father. I remember

00:01:37.840 --> 00:01:42.080
[Amit Varma]: looking at the apartment complex 100 meters away, and wondered what it would be like to

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:48.240
[Amit Varma]: live in an apartment facing that tower. All day, you could look outside the window and

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:52.880
[Amit Varma]: see lives go up in smoke. Well, we are all living in that apartment. And whether you

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:57.940
[Amit Varma]: look outside or you look within, this is what you will see. Life's gone up in smoke in this

00:01:57.940 --> 00:02:04.680
[Amit Varma]: great country of ours in this 21st century.

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:09.840
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:18.360
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:22.360
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is a brilliant economist, Ajay Shah.

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: We discuss the economics and politics of vaccines. Both of us believe that our government made

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:31.960
[Amit Varma]: a tragic error in not getting vaccines out there on a war footing. It spent too much

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:36.760
[Amit Varma]: time. It was hobbled by the ideologies of central planning and Atma Nirbharta, and it

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:41.240
[Amit Varma]: still hasn't learned all the lessons it should have. Ajay helps me get to the heart of the

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:46.080
[Amit Varma]: matter. And I understand the subject much better after this conversation. How could

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.940
[Amit Varma]: we have vaccinated more people? Who should have made these vaccines? How should they

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:54.400
[Amit Varma]: have been distributed? How should we have arrived at a price? We discuss all this in

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:59.280
[Amit Varma]: today's episode, though we spend the first half of it talking about Indian healthcare.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:03.320
[Amit Varma]: Our healthcare system has been broken for decades. It was always going to collapse in

00:03:03.320 --> 00:03:08.920
[Amit Varma]: the face of a challenge like COVID-19. That is why some of us were so terrified in March

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:14.160
[Amit Varma]: last year. We worried about the sort of scenes that we are seeing today in Delhi and elsewhere.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:19.540
[Amit Varma]: We were lucky in April 2020 for a number of reasons to escape that fate. But we should

00:03:19.540 --> 00:03:25.000
[Amit Varma]: have used that time to prepare. And we did not. Well, let's look ahead. What can we do

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.680
[Amit Varma]: now? Healthcare is perhaps the hardest problem to solve in India. So there are no easy answers.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:36.200
[Amit Varma]: But we do need to try and understand the nature of this problem. In his usual lucid style,

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Ajay gave me many insights in this conversation. But before we get to that, let's take a quick

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:48.520
[Amit Varma]: commercial break. Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances are that

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:53.280
[Amit Varma]: many of you first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut, which was active between

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:58.680
[Amit Varma]: 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the form gave

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:04.840
[Amit Varma]: me and I feel I was shaped by it in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle every day and

00:04:04.840 --> 00:04:09.240
[Amit Varma]: was forced to think about many different things because I wrote about many different things.

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:14.320
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons. And now it is time to revive it.

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Only now I'm doing it through a newsletter. I have started the India Uncut newsletter

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:25.720
[Amit Varma]: at indiancut.substack.com where I will write regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:30.620
[Amit Varma]: I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else. So please

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:36.680
[Amit Varma]: do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up,

00:04:36.680 --> 00:04:40.920
[Amit Varma]: each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox. You don't need to

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:48.560
[Amit Varma]: go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:49.560
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:52.880
[Amit Varma]: Ajay, welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:54.960
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for having me here.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:59.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, the last time we spoke was in Feb. In fact, I, you know, I was while setting

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:03.920
[Amit Varma]: the session up, I realized that we recorded on 4th Feb, where we spoke about the farm

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:08.000
[Amit Varma]: bills, which by the way, is one of my top 10 downloaded episodes already. I think it's

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:14.320
[Amit Varma]: moved up to number eight, as of now, a combination both of the urgency of the subject and I would

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:20.480
[Amit Varma]: say the lucidity of your explanations. But interestingly, in that episode, for the first

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:25.480
[Amit Varma]: half, we kind of actually spoke about your new interest in public health and healthcare

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:31.080
[Amit Varma]: and so on, especially in a COVID context. And sadly, the time has kind of come to go

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:35.600
[Amit Varma]: a little deeper into that because of everything that is happening. But before we do that,

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:41.240
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about the recent weeks for you. Where are you? Have you been well?

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:42.800
[Amit Varma]: What's it been like in general?

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:48.600
[Guest]: Mercifully, I've been well, my people have been well. But for the rest, like everybody

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:55.960
[Guest]: else, this is just a nightmare. We keep hearing of friends and friends of friends, person

00:05:55.960 --> 00:06:04.740
[Guest]: x reaches out to person y help find me oxygen help find me an ICU bed. It is a relentless

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:09.840
[Guest]: assault on the soul. You just get exhausted. You just keep wondering and praying. Is there

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:11.280
[Guest]: something we could do different?

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:15.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, there's a new term for this now called doom scrolling, where you just

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:20.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of go on Twitter and you're doom scrolling. You're just it's horrendous. I've never seen

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:24.520
[Amit Varma]: anything like this. And I think, you know, the collective trauma that we're going through

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:29.640
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, in one sense, even greater than partition because it's spread out everywhere

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:37.040
[Amit Varma]: throughout the country. Like, I'm sure every home in this country knows someone who has

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:42.320
[Amit Varma]: suffered or died and so on. And especially when I talk to my friends in Delhi, like everybody

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:46.320
[Amit Varma]: has, you know, is going through shit right now.

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:53.400
[Guest]: I have experienced a very peculiar conflict in my head. And I'm sure you will understand

00:06:53.400 --> 00:07:01.240
[Guest]: it in a flash. And let me just say it. So I'm reminded of the British side in World

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:07.840
[Guest]: War Two, where the binding constraint was the number of pilots. You could do everything

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:12.400
[Guest]: else. You can build planes in a hurry. You can do all kinds of things in a hurry, but

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:17.000
[Guest]: you can't create a good pilot in a hurry. So that's my intuition about thinking about

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:21.240
[Guest]: the health care system. We are where we are. You have a certain amount of doctors, you

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:26.160
[Guest]: have a certain amount of nurses. They're working flat out 18 hours a day. And in the short

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:32.600
[Guest]: run, their supply elasticity is zero. There is nothing you can do to augment the skilled

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:37.920
[Guest]: staff inside the health care facilities. You can do a little bit more quickly in terms

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:44.200
[Guest]: of putting up some ICU beds and some little more oxygen therapy. But fundamentally, in

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:49.480
[Guest]: the short term, it is impossible to change the number of health care workers. In that

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:57.720
[Guest]: case, as a society, as a system, it's curtains. There's 100 beds of capacity. And if there

00:07:57.720 --> 00:08:05.280
[Guest]: are 200 people who require that capacity, then there's just the horrendous choice of

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:11.280
[Guest]: triaging and choosing which 100 are going to get in. And each of us would love to have

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:16.640
[Guest]: our friends and family access those beds. But in system thinking, that's no answer because

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:22.120
[Guest]: any one person that gets in is coming at the expense of somebody else. And how do you make

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:27.640
[Guest]: those moral choices? Similarly, as an economist, it has always been apparent to me that if

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:33.680
[Guest]: you put more money into the problem right now, all that happens is that the demand curve

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:39.760
[Guest]: intersects with the rigid supply curve at a higher price. All you do with a little more

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:44.160
[Guest]: money buying health care services at a time like this is driving up the price. You don't

00:08:44.160 --> 00:08:49.400
[Guest]: change the brute reality, which is that there are 200 people demanding a capacity of 100.

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:52.280
[Guest]: And in the short term, that capacity cannot be changed.

00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:56.240
[Amit Varma]: A few strands. I mean, one, of course, when you speak of the moral choices we have to

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:00.920
[Amit Varma]: make, some of these choices come down totally to privilege and power. For example, there

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:05.480
[Amit Varma]: was this heartbreaking video of this person who'd got an oxygen cylinder for his father

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:09.520
[Amit Varma]: or uncle or whatever, who obviously needed it badly and was going to die. And the cops

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.400
[Amit Varma]: came and they confiscated it from him because they wanted to take it for a VIP, which just

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:19.520
[Amit Varma]: kind of tells you the colonial mindset of the state. And you know, one of the really

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:23.920
[Amit Varma]: heartening things about the last couple of weeks also has another side to it. It's like

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:28.080
[Amit Varma]: the scene and the unseen, which is, you know, on the one hand, it's heartening that everyone

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:32.280
[Amit Varma]: who's reached out on Twitter has just got so much help from people like just now before,

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:37.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, this recording began. And this is like 2pm on April 29. And just before this

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:42.360
[Amit Varma]: recording began, I saw this tweet from my good friend, Joy Bhattacharya, who said that

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:46.360
[Amit Varma]: he knows of at least 12 people who have been helped by reaching out on Twitter, which is

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:50.240
[Amit Varma]: great. But the unseen side of that is that there are 12 other people who didn't get that

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:54.600
[Amit Varma]: help. Because everything is limited. There is an opportunity cost even for that. And

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:59.000
[Amit Varma]: sure, you know, we kind of have the privilege even anyone who can use Twitter and reach

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:04.560
[Amit Varma]: out like that and get amplified also has a certain amount of privilege. And I'm happy

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:10.560
[Amit Varma]: for everyone who's, you know, managed to get help and all of that in these difficult times.

00:10:10.560 --> 00:10:15.400
[Amit Varma]: But the brute reality is that if there are 200 beds and 500 people who need them, 300

00:10:15.400 --> 00:10:20.000
[Amit Varma]: people are just gone. I mean, it's a pretty horrible situation. And last year in March,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.240
[Amit Varma]: I remember, you know, I recorded an episode on COVID, the first of my many episodes on

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:28.840
[Amit Varma]: COVID in general, and my guest in that one was Shruti Rajgopalan. And before we recorded

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:32.920
[Amit Varma]: that episode, you know, as far back as March last year, she was telling me about what could

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:37.440
[Amit Varma]: happen to the healthcare system in India. And from her experiences of her friends in

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:42.200
[Amit Varma]: Italy, where she had lived and all, Bergamo and so on. And it didn't happen. And I thought,

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:46.040
[Amit Varma]: okay, great, we got lucky, you know, whether it was lockdown or a combination of other

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:50.320
[Amit Varma]: factors that people have speculated on, we got lucky it didn't happen. And it's happened

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:53.960
[Amit Varma]: now. And it's happened a year later. And you kind of realize,

00:10:53.960 --> 00:11:00.160
[Guest]: So I think we always knew that the Indian healthcare system doesn't work so well. And

00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:06.360
[Guest]: the capacity in the healthcare system is minuscule. So, you know, in my mind's eye, this was always

00:11:06.360 --> 00:11:15.760
[Guest]: on my mind. I remember, back in February and March 2020, I was writing the first paper

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:20.760
[Guest]: on this subject that I happened to work on. I've written many, many things on the subject.

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:27.200
[Guest]: But my first writing was in February and March, I was writing a paper on the subject. And

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:34.120
[Guest]: my co author and I were kind of playing this out in our mind's eye. And it was just chilling,

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:39.560
[Guest]: because you do the arithmetic, you know, you just multiply through by some plausible hospitalization

00:11:39.560 --> 00:11:46.640
[Guest]: rates by some plausible fatality rates, multiplied by the Indian age structure of the population.

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:49.240
[Amit Varma]: And what you get is quite a disaster.

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:53.200
[Amit Varma]: One of the things that this pandemic has sort of done for us, and I've written a column

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:58.480
[Amit Varma]: on this last year as well, is that it's laid bare a greater ongoing disaster, which is

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:03.840
[Amit Varma]: our dysfunctional flailing state, right? And one subset of that, and not even a subset

00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:08.960
[Amit Varma]: of that, there's a small overlap. But another thing that is laid bare is obviously how,

00:12:08.960 --> 00:12:14.440
[Amit Varma]: what a bad state our healthcare is in. Now, you pointed out about how our healthcare workers

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:18.840
[Amit Varma]: are limited, there are only so many doctors, and there are only so many nurses. And what

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:23.560
[Amit Varma]: they are doing is just incredibly heroic. Most of them going well beyond the call of

00:12:23.560 --> 00:12:27.600
[Amit Varma]: duty and the kind of risks they take and the kind of service they're putting in, but they're

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:33.400
[Amit Varma]: limited. Give me a sense now, that if you look at it outside the context of the pandemic,

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:37.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, how can we quantify the shortcomings in our healthcare system, especially in something

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:42.060
[Amit Varma]: like this? Like, are there figures that you know, in a developed country, there would

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:47.160
[Amit Varma]: be so many doctors plus 1000 people in the population, so many nurses or whatever? Are

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:53.000
[Amit Varma]: there quantifiable ways to think about how in terms of healthcare we are so far behind?

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:58.040
[Guest]: Here, I'm afraid I'm going to go all economist on you. So this is about money. This is about

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:05.080
[Guest]: affluence. It's about how much you're willing to spend. So it turns on the ratio between

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:10.280
[Guest]: the income of a doctor and the income of the general population. Okay, so if you live in

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:15.920
[Guest]: a country where your income is good vis-a-vis a doctor's income, then you're going to fare

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:19.560
[Guest]: relatively well, because using your income, you're going to be able to buy many man hours

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:24.600
[Guest]: of a doctor's time, and vice versa. So now the large mass of the Indian population has

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:32.680
[Guest]: an income, where, frankly, meaningful levels of training in the doctor are unaffordable.

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:37.560
[Guest]: So I classify that as a poverty problem. I classify that as an underdevelopment problem,

00:13:37.560 --> 00:13:44.360
[Guest]: that it is just baked in. It is inevitable that when we're a poor country, and because

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:50.000
[Guest]: building a doctor is like building an RAF pilot is something that takes thousands of

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:55.880
[Guest]: hours of training, it's a considerable investment. And it's not possible to make a particularly

00:13:55.880 --> 00:14:01.720
[Guest]: cheap doctor. We can try. We need to improve processes and bring down the cost of healthcare.

00:14:01.720 --> 00:14:08.560
[Guest]: We need more telemedicine. We need more AI-based diagnosis systems backed by just a nurse.

00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:12.760
[Guest]: They are all great directions to go in. But the brute fact is that there is a poverty

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:17.760
[Guest]: problem. So I think those, the metrics that you refer to are a bit dangerous, because

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:24.360
[Guest]: we slip into a first world way of thinking. And that's not a fair comparison against where

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:28.720
[Guest]: we are in India today. So in India today, we should be asking the question that at Indian

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:33.920
[Guest]: levels of income, what can you do different? And in my opinion, we need to do a revolution

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:39.600
[Guest]: in AI plus nurse rather than a doctor, because for the foreseeable future, there's not going

00:14:39.600 --> 00:14:44.160
[Guest]: to be a doctor. We need to do much more with telemedicine. And again, the telemedicine

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:48.640
[Guest]: can be some hybrid of a doctor or an AI at the other end. It doesn't even have to be

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:55.120
[Guest]: a human being all the time. And then we turn to healthcare system design. And this turns

00:14:55.120 --> 00:15:02.160
[Guest]: on problems like what's the nature of the market failure in healthcare? And the market

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:09.400
[Guest]: failure of healthcare is basically a crisis of asymmetric information. When you are faced

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:14.280
[Guest]: with a hospital and the hospital says that your mother needs a ventilator, and if you

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:17.760
[Guest]: don't sign on this piece of paper right now, she's going to die. What are you going to

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:26.520
[Guest]: do? So there is extreme mis-selling by private healthcare providers. And the question is,

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:31.520
[Guest]: how do we reorganize healthcare so as to address that market failure and produce better behavior

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:36.320
[Guest]: out of private providers? And then somewhere in this, the least important element of the

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:43.800
[Guest]: Indian healthcare system is there is one large PSU who's called the government. So the government

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:50.800
[Guest]: is not thinking health policy. The government is thinking I'm one big PSU. So there is many,

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:55.520
[Guest]: many government hospitals. There are many, many government departments of health, and

00:15:55.520 --> 00:16:00.880
[Guest]: they seem to concentrate on being a PSU. So think of an old department of telecom, which

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:06.120
[Guest]: was thinking that they are in the telephony business. That's the Indian health establishment.

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:11.880
[Guest]: And this is part of the story about why we do so badly on health policy, because the

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:16.880
[Guest]: DNA of the Indian health policy community is to look at the world from the worldview

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:24.620
[Guest]: of a healthcare PSU. And they are not used to worrying about their own operational capabilities

00:16:24.620 --> 00:16:28.480
[Guest]: and efficiency. And they are used to just always asking for more money. So their answer

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:33.160
[Guest]: is always more money. If you speak to any conventional health expert in India, the story

00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: is give me more money. And that's not a very useful way to approach it. Because neither

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.600
[Guest]: does the healthcare PSU work too well, nor does the private sector healthcare work too

00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:49.480
[Guest]: well. So, you know, we are caught between two bad things that are happening in the country.

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:55.040
[Guest]: And that's the essence of what is wrong with Indian healthcare today. The puzzle, the thinking

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:59.600
[Guest]: challenge, the research challenge is how to understand this landscape, how to create the

00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:06.000
[Guest]: data sets that will support the research on this landscape, and how to find our way out

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:11.000
[Guest]: of this problem. And I don't pretend to have the answers. But I am at this level of knowledge

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.080
[Guest]: that I am able to succinctly pose the questions.

00:17:14.080 --> 00:17:18.440
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating, because I was going to take a couple of strands and ask you for potential

00:17:18.440 --> 00:17:22.560
[Amit Varma]: answers for that. And I'm going to try and do that anyway. And one of those strands is

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:27.680
[Amit Varma]: this that just as Indians understand that there is no rule of law effectively in this

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:33.040
[Amit Varma]: country for most people, unless you're incredibly privileged. You know, people have Jugaadu

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:37.320
[Amit Varma]: ways of getting by their social trust, and all of those things come into play. Similarly,

00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:41.160
[Amit Varma]: there isn't really a healthcare system, a functional healthcare system in the sense

00:17:41.160 --> 00:17:46.160
[Amit Varma]: that most individuals in this country are one medical emergency away from just going

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:49.960
[Amit Varma]: broke. You know, that's just a fact of the matter. You know, I've written about, you

00:17:49.960 --> 00:17:54.320
[Amit Varma]: know, so many other problems India's face, but this is one field where I haven't quite

00:17:54.320 --> 00:17:58.600
[Amit Varma]: gotten and handled on the structural problems. For example, we can look at something like

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:02.440
[Amit Varma]: education and say that, okay, here's a structural problem, the incentives for the state are

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:08.160
[Amit Varma]: bad in terms of provision, and it should just allow far more private provision and just

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:13.240
[Amit Varma]: let society solve its own problems while simultaneously trying to beef up state capacity and do what

00:18:13.240 --> 00:18:17.880
[Amit Varma]: it's doing. Similarly, you know, we've discussed the problems of agriculture in our last episode,

00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:22.160
[Amit Varma]: and I've, you know, gone deeper into it in previous episodes before that. But what is

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:27.000
[Amit Varma]: the problem with healthcare? Because in the eyes of the common man, you're just in denial

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.080
[Amit Varma]: that you're ever going to fall ill. You know, just as we have an illusion of immortality,

00:18:31.080 --> 00:18:35.920
[Amit Varma]: which keeps us away from thinking about the fact that we have a limited time span, although

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:41.160
[Amit Varma]: sadly in the last few days, I think many more people have had occasion to ponder on that.

00:18:41.160 --> 00:18:45.360
[Amit Varma]: But just as we have that illusion of immortality, and we live as you're going to live forever,

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:49.040
[Amit Varma]: we also have this illusion of good health. And we are in denial of the fact that someday

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:54.200
[Amit Varma]: we will require medical help. And the impression most people will have of say, private medical

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:58.960
[Amit Varma]: health in India is that it's almost like a scam, almost like a racket. I think Rana Das

00:18:58.960 --> 00:19:03.040
[Amit Varma]: Gupta wrote a book about this a few years ago about the situation in Delhi that you

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:07.560
[Amit Varma]: go to any of these big hospitals, and they'll give you hazard tests, which you don't require,

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:12.440
[Amit Varma]: and they'll completely fleece you. And their incentives are tailored towards doing that

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:16.440
[Amit Varma]: doctors incentives are tailored towards prescribing more and more tests. So the hospital makes

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:21.640
[Amit Varma]: money and blah, blah, blah, and everything seems kind of broken. And of course, the public

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:27.640
[Amit Varma]: healthcare in India is the worst. So the answer is, isn't even that. So structurally, what

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:32.800
[Amit Varma]: are the problems that they are and given the poverty, you know, are they solvable? Or do

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:34.760
[Guest]: we need to solve for poverty first?

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:41.560
[Guest]: So again, I will go all economist on you that whatever x rupees are being spent, the puzzle

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:45.000
[Guest]: is on how to get the most bang for the buck. Okay, so I just treat the poverty problem

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:49.960
[Guest]: as given, okay, one day, we're gonna get rich, and that'll get better. So it is incredibly

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:56.680
[Guest]: important to push for broad GDP growth is the greatest weapon to solve all these problems.

00:19:56.680 --> 00:20:03.280
[Guest]: But right now, let's stick to an allocative problem. I have a funny story. The year was

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:10.560
[Guest]: 2004. I was sitting with my dear friends, Jeff Hammer and Lance Pritchett. At the time,

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:16.560
[Guest]: my mind used to be filled with macroeconomics and finance. And we were doing a furious conversation

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest]: around some of old things, some of those things. And at some point, both of them stopped and

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.160
[Guest]: said, you know, Ajay, you're a very smart guy. You think you're thinking a lot about

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:29.680
[Guest]: macro and finance. But you know what, when you grow up, you're going to have to do health.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:36.200
[Guest]: And I was like, huh. And they said, everything that you're doing is trivial. And the really

00:20:36.200 --> 00:20:42.920
[Guest]: hard problem is health, that actually, you know, fixing monetary policy, doing an inflation

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:46.680
[Guest]: targeting system with the Monetary Policy Committee and narrow down the function of

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:47.680
[Guest]: the central bank.

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:52.000
[Guest]: It's kind of obvious, and it's really not hard. There's just some pesky political problems

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.840
[Guest]: you have to solve. But it's not really hard. It's kind of trivial. Similarly, you want

00:20:55.840 --> 00:21:00.560
[Guest]: to do international trade. Frankly, you know, at the end of the tunnel, there's basically

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:04.760
[Guest]: only one thing to do, which is remove all trade barriers. Okay, you can do it in an

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:08.480
[Guest]: obfuscated way, you can do it in a complicated way, but there's really nothing hard there,

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:16.640
[Guest]: and so on. Whereas, the truly difficult thing is health. Why? In my opinion, the pieces

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:17.640
[Guest]: of it are as follows.

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:22.640
[Guest]: The first is that there is such a profound amount of asymmetric information. You and

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:27.240
[Guest]: I really don't know what the doctor does. You and I really don't know the marginal contribution

00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:33.040
[Guest]: of a doctor. To kind of make an education analogy, in education, we like to think that

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:39.360
[Guest]: we'll pay for test results. But there is the ever-present problem that some part of the

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:44.960
[Guest]: test results are baked in because of the child at home and family. And some of the test results

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:50.120
[Guest]: are the contribution of the teacher. So, for example, a school running in a slum will always

00:21:50.120 --> 00:21:54.120
[Guest]: generate low test scores. And if we think we're going to pay something proportional

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:59.520
[Guest]: to the test scores, then we're doing something very unfair. So, it's very hard to disentangle

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:06.000
[Guest]: the contribution of the healthcare. You and I, as individual customers, are not very wise

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:14.360
[Guest]: in how we think of our healthcare providers. Too many of us go to quacks. We endlessly

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:20.440
[Guest]: submit to all kinds of nonsense where there is some alternative therapy or the other,

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:25.040
[Guest]: and we tend to take it more seriously than we should. Or we tend to care about a bedside

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:30.600
[Guest]: manner. We tend to think that a doctor who speaks nicely to me is a nice doctor. We tend

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:34.400
[Guest]: to think that a doctor who speaks in English knows more than a doctor who does not speak

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:38.840
[Guest]: in English, and so on. There is a hundred cognitive biases that are in play. And we

00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:44.160
[Guest]: are all very smug, and we've persuaded ourselves that we understand this stuff, whereas actually

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:49.080
[Guest]: we don't. And that creates all the wrong incentives. So, hospitals have incentives to look like

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:54.920
[Guest]: five-star hotels, but that's not essential to the business of being a hospital. To be

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:59.320
[Guest]: a good hospital, you need to be clean, but you don't need to be like a five-star hotel.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:05.880
[Guest]: Whereas the modern Indian healthcare industry is really building some expensive infrastructure

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:11.160
[Guest]: and loaning it out, renting it out to one doctor or one specialist after another. And

00:23:11.160 --> 00:23:17.120
[Guest]: customers are just going by the glitz in the brand name and the marble foyer rather than

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:22.400
[Guest]: the substantive content of the knowledge and the value add of the healthcare. There are

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:27.440
[Guest]: important regional differences in some of these problems. So, some of my friends have

00:23:27.440 --> 00:23:32.440
[Guest]: invested in many healthcare companies. They have purchased and successfully built and

00:23:32.440 --> 00:23:38.960
[Guest]: exited many healthcare companies. And I remember one of the partners said to me that he has

00:23:38.960 --> 00:23:43.600
[Guest]: never felt comfortable about buying a healthcare establishment in North India, because he felt

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:48.200
[Guest]: there is a pervasive ethical collapse in North India of the kind that you don't see in the

00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:53.000
[Guest]: other parts of the country. So, in the West and the South, there is still a little more

00:23:53.000 --> 00:24:00.320
[Guest]: of the ideal of a doctor as a service provider, of a doctor as a good person that is going

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:05.800
[Guest]: to take care of you. Whereas in North India, there seems to be a bigger collapse into just

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:12.520
[Guest]: craven commercial considerations, where a doctor misprescribes drugs and tests and gets

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:17.400
[Guest]: a kickback. Amusingly enough, I want to say that in the field of finance, we've gone after

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:24.080
[Guest]: kickbacks. We do more with mutual funds and insurance companies in blocking the kickbacks

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:31.240
[Guest]: from a manufacturer to the sales agent. Whereas in the field of medicine, we do nothing. We

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:37.320
[Guest]: do absolutely nothing today in blocking these kickbacks. And I consider these kickbacks

00:24:37.320 --> 00:24:40.960
[Guest]: highly unethical, but they are the norm and not the exception.

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:46.800
[Guest]: Another anecdote, one of my colleagues in Delhi was experiencing a certain class of

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:54.040
[Guest]: concerns and she spoke with a person in Bombay on this question, who was a doctor. And the

00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:58.320
[Guest]: feedback I got was that she should buy a ticket and come to Bombay and do this entire thing

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:02.920
[Guest]: in Bombay. They don't do it in Delhi because the healthcare establishment in Delhi is so

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:07.680
[Guest]: bad, it's so dangerous. Do your work in Bombay. There's more decency, there's more ethics,

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:13.200
[Guest]: there's more fair play in Bombay. Last anecdote, if I had a horrendous life-threatening situation,

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:17.280
[Guest]: what would I like to do? I'd like to buy a ticket and go to Christian Medical College,

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:21.640
[Guest]: Vellore. This is an old-fashioned place where doctors are paid a fixed salary and there

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:26.200
[Guest]: are no kickbacks. And in my opinion, it's the best healthcare in India.

00:25:26.200 --> 00:25:33.520
[Guest]: So the profound asymmetry between the healthcare provider and the customer really poses a difficult

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:39.200
[Guest]: challenge for market-based thinking. And we in India are in some peculiar place where

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:44.840
[Guest]: there are some noble establishments like Christian Medical College, Vellore. There are some parts

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:49.560
[Guest]: of the country and there are some organizations who care more about the well-being of patients

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:54.560
[Guest]: and seem to do a better job. And then there is most of India, which is in a wasteland

00:25:54.560 --> 00:26:00.800
[Guest]: of kickbacks and all the wrong incentives for doctors. Somewhere in this, we have to

00:26:00.800 --> 00:26:09.560
[Guest]: bring in the distinction between the medicalization of healthcare and the problem of wellness.

00:26:09.560 --> 00:26:13.160
[Guest]: If you pause to think about it, I think we spoke about it last time in the farm bills

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:17.720
[Guest]: thing, prevention is a thousand times better than cure. And you just come back at this

00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:25.160
[Guest]: over and over and over. All of us should be prioritizing wellness a thousand times more

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:31.880
[Guest]: than we do with the healthcare. And in wellness, I would always go beyond the physical body

00:26:31.880 --> 00:26:38.200
[Guest]: to the mind for two reasons. First is that because a healthy mind fosters a healthy body.

00:26:38.200 --> 00:26:42.560
[Guest]: And the second is because the purpose of living is to have some peace of mind and happiness,

00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:47.200
[Guest]: which is a mental state. It's not a physical state. So really the whole point of us being

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:54.000
[Guest]: alive and seeking utility and maximizing utils is about a state of mind. It's about having

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:59.360
[Guest]: peace of mind, being comfortable with what you are doing, finding meaning and purpose

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:04.160
[Guest]: in your life rather than being on a treadmill. So these problems are intricately connected

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:09.400
[Guest]: to the state of health of the person. A lot of the hard driving people who are extremely

00:27:09.400 --> 00:27:14.880
[Guest]: ambitious are actually very messed up, both in terms of the state of mind and in the state

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:19.520
[Guest]: of body. So these are difficult, difficult problems. And the present Indian healthcare

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:24.040
[Guest]: establishment has no interest at all in you as a human being. They don't want to talk

00:27:24.040 --> 00:27:29.640
[Guest]: about your state of stress and your unhealthy lifestyle. And what you really need a lot

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:33.640
[Guest]: of the time is a good talking to by a wise person saying, dude, you need to fix your

00:27:33.640 --> 00:27:38.080
[Guest]: life. Instead, the healthcare provider is saying, yeah, come here. I'll put you under

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:41.840
[Guest]: the knife and I'll fix you up. And sure enough, two years from now, you're going to be messed

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:47.440
[Guest]: up again. This is a profoundly different perspective that I think we need to bring to bear on our

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:53.240
[Guest]: lives as individuals. But putting our heads into it as thinkers and economists and thinking

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:59.520
[Guest]: about the state and society, it is very difficult to create the correct incentives for a healthcare

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:04.640
[Guest]: system that would even pause to think about these things. Because for the healthcare provider,

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:09.760
[Guest]: it's literally how many rupees can I make per minute? So becoming avuncular and having

00:28:09.760 --> 00:28:12.520
[Guest]: a good conversation with you is not that person's incentive.

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:17.340
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And it strikes me that there's an intersection of different domains here, which are kind

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:23.480
[Amit Varma]: of separate, like obviously one of those domains is this mental wellness stuff and all of that.

00:28:23.480 --> 00:28:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And a doctor who's there to treat the body who's been trained in say, cardiology or,

00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:31.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, vascular disease or whatever might well say that look, I've been trained in this

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:35.720
[Amit Varma]: and this is what I will do the treatment in and the wellness is for other folks and I

00:28:35.720 --> 00:28:40.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of get that. The other two sort of different domains and you'd elaborated on this last

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:44.520
[Amit Varma]: time and I intend to ask you about it after this question is of course, the two separate

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:48.200
[Amit Varma]: domains of public health and healthcare where public health really falls into prevention

00:28:48.200 --> 00:28:53.240
[Amit Varma]: and should be the responsibility of the state. And healthcare is much more of a kind of private

00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:58.160
[Amit Varma]: thing. But my specific question about the private situation remains in the sense that,

00:28:58.160 --> 00:29:02.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, everybody wants to make money. Everybody's greedy, not just the doctors, you know, I

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:06.720
[Amit Varma]: am greedy, you are greedy in different ways. And everybody's not necessarily greedy for

00:29:06.720 --> 00:29:10.140
[Amit Varma]: money, but that's fine. You want to make money? How do you make money? You make money by making

00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:14.720
[Amit Varma]: someone else's life better off. It's a positive sum game. The incentives are good. Here, of

00:29:14.720 --> 00:29:20.360
[Amit Varma]: course, the incentives are kind of the problem because the asymmetric information is getting

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:23.240
[Amit Varma]: in the way because patients don't know what's good for them. They have no option but to

00:29:23.240 --> 00:29:28.040
[Amit Varma]: listen to what the doctor prescribes and the doctor will, you know, go down all of these

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:31.920
[Amit Varma]: roads where he gets maximum kickback and all that and they're responding to incentives.

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:36.160
[Amit Varma]: I guess there are two key questions. One is what can be done to change the situation of

00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:40.360
[Amit Varma]: asymmetric information, like you're saying in other fields like finance and all things

00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:45.440
[Amit Varma]: have been done and they're working to whatever extent and more importantly, how do you change

00:29:45.440 --> 00:29:49.800
[Amit Varma]: the incentives like in any other domain that I think about the way to change the incentives

00:29:49.800 --> 00:29:55.840
[Amit Varma]: is that you let competition thrive and competition is the best regulation and you know, the incentives

00:29:55.840 --> 00:30:01.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of fall into place and by letting competition thrive, I mean, I don't just mean markets,

00:30:01.080 --> 00:30:05.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean free markets. People often mix it up in India where we don't have free markets

00:30:05.200 --> 00:30:09.000
[Amit Varma]: and anything at all. There is more and more cronyism where the whole idea is that big

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:13.520
[Amit Varma]: corporates want to keep competition out. But ideally, if you want to get the incentives

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:17.880
[Amit Varma]: right, you want to keep cronyism at bay, you want to keep state power at bay, you want

00:30:17.880 --> 00:30:22.320
[Amit Varma]: the rule of law to be maintained, but you want competition. But in healthcare, the answer

00:30:22.320 --> 00:30:26.520
[Amit Varma]: doesn't seem so simple. Like you said, for people who think about the world through this

00:30:26.520 --> 00:30:33.160
[Amit Varma]: prism of voluntary action, positive sum games, competition, right incentives, all of that,

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:36.200
[Amit Varma]: somewhere it doesn't seem to apply, there is some problem. That's what I'm trying to

00:30:36.200 --> 00:30:41.520
[Amit Varma]: put my finger on. So if I ask you to get specific, you know, what would that be?

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:49.080
[Guest]: The first piece would be that we are at the infancy in terms of studying and understanding

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:55.320
[Guest]: this field. And the first desperate need is more data. So we just don't know enough about

00:30:55.320 --> 00:31:00.520
[Guest]: this field. So I recall many other fields where I have worked on in previous years,

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:06.120
[Guest]: generally, when the work program began, there was a fair evidentiary base. So there is a

00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:12.120
[Guest]: burning crisis in this field, which is the lack of data. So we need to go into the reality

00:31:12.120 --> 00:31:18.160
[Guest]: of India, where there is 60, 70, 80% private healthcare, and the remainder is public healthcare.

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:22.680
[Guest]: And we need to do measurement, measurement, measurement, make data sets and release them.

00:31:22.680 --> 00:31:27.040
[Guest]: And maybe for 10, 20 years, that's all that we are able to do. And out of that will come

00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:32.640
[Guest]: better knowledge. This is my first sense of what is it that should practically be done.

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:36.800
[Guest]: The first thing that needs to be done is we need to build data sets about what's actually

00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:44.080
[Guest]: happening on the ground in the field of health. My second thought is that what we need is

00:31:44.080 --> 00:31:50.800
[Guest]: sophisticated buyers who will exert countervailing force against sellers. Okay, so you and me

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:57.000
[Guest]: as customers, it doesn't work too well. I would readily have gone down the path of thinking

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:01.400
[Guest]: is there a role for the state and could you build some regulatory capacity? Could you

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:06.880
[Guest]: build some product liability, some tort law? And you should do a little bit of it, because

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:13.040
[Guest]: there is a role for some amount of liability and law and, you know, for example, just shutting

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:20.680
[Guest]: down the kickbacks is going to need force of law. So there is a need for tort law and

00:32:20.680 --> 00:32:26.560
[Guest]: some amount of regulation. I say this softly, because at present, the project of the Indian

00:32:26.560 --> 00:32:32.040
[Guest]: Regulatory State, the Indian Administrative State is really not working. So we need to

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:36.640
[Guest]: get to it at some point, but I'm not optimistic that that time is now, because right now that

00:32:36.640 --> 00:32:42.360
[Guest]: project is in a bit of shambles. It's really working very poorly all across the landscape.

00:32:42.360 --> 00:32:49.520
[Guest]: We're not succeeding on the business of law, courts, judiciary, enforcement, regulators,

00:32:49.520 --> 00:32:55.120
[Guest]: regulation, regulators, of course, private people. I used to be more optimistic about

00:32:55.120 --> 00:33:00.560
[Guest]: that agenda a while ago. Today, I think we've run aground and we need to really pick ourselves

00:33:00.560 --> 00:33:05.280
[Guest]: up and make some of those basics work. And at a future date, it could have a significant

00:33:05.280 --> 00:33:11.440
[Guest]: role in the field of health as well. And that's what brings me to sophisticated buyers. It

00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:15.560
[Guest]: seems to me that the most useful thing to do today is to build a cadre of sophisticated

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:23.160
[Guest]: buyers and it can work in two ways. Basically, think of a health insurance company that says

00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:29.680
[Guest]: to you that you give me X rupees a month and I'm responsible for all your health care.

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:35.360
[Guest]: And imagine we do enough work around that sentence so that they don't actually shortchange

00:33:35.360 --> 00:33:42.080
[Guest]: you. Because all too often in India, the health insurance company is just rejecting your claims

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:45.600
[Guest]: and is saying, sorry, I'm not going to pay. Assume for a moment that we found our way

00:33:45.600 --> 00:33:51.560
[Guest]: through that. And then that health insurance company is able to be a tough, sophisticated

00:33:51.560 --> 00:34:00.760
[Guest]: buyer that can have negotiating power against health care organizations and can generate

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:05.720
[Guest]: better outcomes for the customer, can fight for the customer, can act for the customer.

00:34:05.720 --> 00:34:10.880
[Guest]: Otherwise, right now, you and I are just in a very bad bargaining position when we step

00:34:10.880 --> 00:34:19.360
[Guest]: into a hospital. And the more urgent and the more heartrending the situation, the greater

00:34:19.360 --> 00:34:24.960
[Guest]: is the extent to which we are likely to just go along and say yes to something that an

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:30.920
[Guest]: employee of the hospital says. And that's unfortunately not a very good thing. I mentioned

00:34:30.920 --> 00:34:37.080
[Guest]: a health maintenance organization, an HMO, which in the limit is a consortium of health

00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:44.600
[Guest]: care organizations and insurance, where it all comes together that you sign on for a

00:34:44.600 --> 00:34:49.960
[Guest]: comprehensive agreement and they take care of you for life. They have specified clinical

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:55.360
[Guest]: protocols through which they will deliver health care to you. And we need to worry about

00:34:55.360 --> 00:35:01.360
[Guest]: consumer protection because they also have an incentive to underspend on your care. But

00:35:01.360 --> 00:35:05.840
[Guest]: it seems to me that that's a good direction worth going in. And in India, the cutting

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:11.480
[Guest]: edge of this is insurance. But then you get into my old beat, which is insurance companies

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:17.840
[Guest]: and insurance regulation. And I have a fairly gloomy feeling about the state of capability

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:25.000
[Guest]: either in IRDA or in the insurance companies. So, none of these pathways are readily open

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:29.800
[Guest]: in India right now. They are all difficult, long journeys. That doesn't mean you should

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:35.240
[Guest]: not do them. So, if you tell me that a tree is going to take 20 years to fruition, I'll

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:40.720
[Guest]: say let's run out and plant it right now. So, it seems to me that work on data, work

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:46.920
[Guest]: on insurance companies, work on insurance regulation. These are the highest priorities

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:48.840
[Amit Varma]: in thinking about health care in India today.

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:52.880
[Amit Varma]: So, a couple of questions that arise from this. One is, you spoke about the need for

00:35:52.880 --> 00:35:57.800
[Amit Varma]: data about, you know, we need to gather data better. We need more specific data sets and

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:01.480
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. And I just recorded an episode yesterday, which will actually go

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:05.760
[Amit Varma]: out after yours because, you know, vaccination is a more urgent subject. But I chatted with

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:10.960
[Amit Varma]: Gautam Menon, incredibly insightful episode. And if I remember correctly, I hope I'm not

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:15.880
[Amit Varma]: getting the source wrong. One of the things he spoke about in the episode was the data

00:36:15.880 --> 00:36:21.240
[Amit Varma]: that we have in terms of cause of death. You know, about 80% of India won't give a, the

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:25.720
[Amit Varma]: deaths aren't recorded with a cause and blah, blah, blah. And the percentage where you actually

00:36:25.720 --> 00:36:30.120
[Amit Varma]: know the cause of death that has happened is just something ludicrously low and therefore

00:36:30.120 --> 00:36:35.040
[Amit Varma]: is not useful in any way. So, I understand that. And especially in the context of COVID,

00:36:35.040 --> 00:36:37.040
[Amit Varma]: what we're seeing around us where, sorry.

00:36:37.040 --> 00:36:46.240
[Guest]: Causes of death is an exotic frontier in India today. Counting the dead is the immediate

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:51.560
[Guest]: battle. You go to New York City, you get a website where every day the number of dead

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:58.400
[Guest]: are reported. That data is exotic in India today. You just don't have the number of deaths

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:02.720
[Guest]: in India. So, the municipalities know what's happening in the crematoriums, but they don't

00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:07.320
[Guest]: release. So, basic health data infrastructure in India is lacking.

00:37:07.320 --> 00:37:12.200
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. And we are seeing that around us in these COVID times where not only don't

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:16.120
[Amit Varma]: we have accurate data about what's going on now, but it is likely that part of the reason

00:37:16.120 --> 00:37:20.640
[Amit Varma]: for this present crisis was that we didn't get accurate data during the first wave as

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:25.160
[Amit Varma]: it were. And because we didn't understand the extent of the spread of the pandemic and

00:37:25.160 --> 00:37:29.640
[Amit Varma]: the damage it caused, we didn't prepare as much as we should have. We weren't as alarmed

00:37:29.640 --> 00:37:34.200
[Amit Varma]: as we should have been. We got complacent. But my specific question to you is this, that

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:39.200
[Amit Varma]: what kind of data sets are we talking about specifically? And what is the concrete difference

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:45.200
[Amit Varma]: that they make? You know that if you get X data, we'll be able to do Y thing or understand

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:49.140
[Amit Varma]: this aspect of the system better and make it better and pieces fall into place. Give

00:37:49.140 --> 00:37:52.360
[Amit Varma]: me a sense of that with specifics if it's possible.

00:37:52.360 --> 00:37:59.080
[Guest]: What works is to just think blow by blow about the activities in a system of interest and

00:37:59.080 --> 00:38:03.560
[Guest]: then just think of putting numbers to the whole thing. That's how we think of data sets.

00:38:03.560 --> 00:38:09.200
[Guest]: So let's start. Are people getting sick? Are people feeling well? Are people feeling healthy

00:38:09.200 --> 00:38:14.320
[Guest]: is the first basic question. So you will get evidence about the extent to which people

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:19.160
[Guest]: say, I'm not feeling good today. And you will start looking at this on a map. You'll get

00:38:19.160 --> 00:38:23.520
[Guest]: a heat map of where people are unwell in India. Is it younger people? Is it older people?

00:38:23.520 --> 00:38:27.680
[Guest]: And so on. Right there, you will see some public health stories where arsenic in the

00:38:27.680 --> 00:38:33.080
[Guest]: water makes you more unhealthy. And you know, it suggests public health interventions. OK,

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:38.880
[Guest]: fine. Then a person is feeling bad to the point where they seek health care. So I'd

00:38:38.880 --> 00:38:42.960
[Guest]: like to know, you know, do different people have different psychological and affluence

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:47.920
[Guest]: trigger points for seeking health care? Very important to know that. What's the point at

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:53.200
[Guest]: which you decide that I'm going to go seek health care? What's the fever at which you

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:57.640
[Guest]: think it's OK to go to work? What's the fever at which you think it's not OK to go to work?

00:38:57.640 --> 00:39:02.280
[Guest]: And then you decide that, OK, this is really no good. I've been down for three whole days.

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:06.720
[Guest]: Now I need to go find health care. OK, then do you choose to go to a private facility?

00:39:06.720 --> 00:39:11.160
[Guest]: Do you choose to go to a public facility? Then think of fine grained data where you

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:16.000
[Guest]: have the GPS cards of the household and the GPS cards of the provider and what determines

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:20.600
[Guest]: provider choice. OK, then you need to start creating data sets that understand there are

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:25.600
[Guest]: different categories of providers. There are complete quacks. You call it whatever you

00:39:25.600 --> 00:39:32.200
[Guest]: call it, ayurvedic or homeopathic or uncertified or whatever. There's all kinds of quacks in

00:39:32.200 --> 00:39:36.800
[Guest]: the landscape. Do you go to quacks or do you go to something that claims some semblance

00:39:36.800 --> 00:39:41.240
[Guest]: of a medical education? And then, of course, there are medical colleges in India that do

00:39:41.240 --> 00:39:46.640
[Guest]: next to nothing in terms of teaching people. So what's the human capital of the provider

00:39:46.640 --> 00:39:51.840
[Guest]: and what shapes the choice of the individual? How does an individual choose? So is it that

00:39:51.840 --> 00:39:56.120
[Guest]: if there are two children in the house, there's a boy and there's a girl and the household

00:39:56.120 --> 00:40:01.680
[Guest]: has different trigger points for the boy to get health care and the boy gets sent to some

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:07.440
[Guest]: serious MBBS doctor and the girl gets taken to a quack? OK, so what happens in the behavior

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:11.600
[Guest]: and the decision making of the household? Then what was the behavior and the decision

00:40:11.600 --> 00:40:18.960
[Guest]: making of the providers that Jeff Hammers has once said to me that in his research on

00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:27.740
[Guest]: India and medical care, here is his description of what actually happens in the modal conversation

00:40:27.740 --> 00:40:33.480
[Guest]: between a health care professional and a patient. The patient goes and sits in a chair. The

00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:39.800
[Guest]: health care professional utters two words, which in Hindi are, kya hai? OK, that's all,

00:40:39.800 --> 00:40:45.520
[Guest]: which is what do you have? And the person says something about what symptoms that person

00:40:45.520 --> 00:40:49.880
[Guest]: is suffering. The doctor scribbles a prescription, hands over the prescription. That's it. That's

00:40:49.880 --> 00:40:54.840
[Guest]: all that happens by way of conversation and asks for some money. And this is it. This

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:59.920
[Guest]: is all health care interaction. So can we study these health care interactions? Do certain

00:40:59.920 --> 00:41:05.680
[Guest]: kind of symptoms generate a different investigative tree on the part of the provider? Do certain

00:41:05.680 --> 00:41:11.480
[Guest]: kind of patients go down a different investigative tree? If I speak in English with the doctor,

00:41:11.480 --> 00:41:16.280
[Guest]: does the doctor treat me differently from if I speak in Marathi? OK, so these are all

00:41:16.280 --> 00:41:20.240
[Guest]: the interesting questions to pursue that Jeff has always said to me that there are many

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:24.680
[Guest]: doctors in India who know a lot and they exercise their discretion and choose when to put their

00:41:24.680 --> 00:41:29.480
[Guest]: knowledge into play. So it's not like the doctor is going to put full effort on every

00:41:29.480 --> 00:41:34.760
[Guest]: single patient. The doctor has a notion that there is a patient where I'm just going to

00:41:34.760 --> 00:41:39.280
[Guest]: spend two minutes and get 200 rupees and not really going to try. Whereas for certain patients,

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:44.160
[Guest]: I'm going to take more effort. And then finally, you get to the holy grail, which is that to

00:41:44.160 --> 00:41:50.680
[Guest]: what extent did the visit to a health care professional make a marginal difference to

00:41:50.680 --> 00:41:55.280
[Guest]: making the person better off? And that can be viewed in many different ways. As all of

00:41:55.280 --> 00:41:59.320
[Guest]: us know, in a large fraction of problems, if you're just going to sit home and do absolutely

00:41:59.320 --> 00:42:03.920
[Guest]: nothing, odds are you're going to get better. And under many, many circumstances, the human

00:42:03.920 --> 00:42:07.880
[Guest]: just gets better. So you need to think about treatment and control where case one, the

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:11.400
[Guest]: person does absolutely nothing. Case two, the person goes to a health care provider.

00:42:11.400 --> 00:42:17.480
[Guest]: Did you get better or did you get mis-prescribed some bad things? And did it actually do damage

00:42:17.480 --> 00:42:21.600
[Guest]: to your life? And then finally, you go closer to the wellness question that to what extent

00:42:21.600 --> 00:42:27.560
[Guest]: do episodes of health care create conditions for going towards higher wellness versus to

00:42:27.560 --> 00:42:33.520
[Guest]: what extent do interactions with the health care business generate a mere medicalization?

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:38.160
[Guest]: So you just go back over and over and keep going through one bout of medicalization after

00:42:38.160 --> 00:42:44.240
[Guest]: another. So this is a sort of flow perspective of thinking from the viewpoint of one household.

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:48.960
[Guest]: Think of all the things that they do and imagine in some dream world where we measure, measure,

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:52.960
[Guest]: measure, measure. And we think about how different kinds of health care establishments, different

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:58.400
[Guest]: kinds of tariff structures, presence of an insurance company as a counterweight in negotiating

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:02.760
[Guest]: power, does it change the behavior of the hospital and so on. So these are all the research

00:43:02.760 --> 00:43:06.200
[Guest]: questions that can flow from this kind of detailed, comprehensive measurement.

00:43:06.200 --> 00:43:10.320
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous. And I guess if this data is all publicly available, then what also happens

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:14.960
[Amit Varma]: is that entrepreneurs everywhere get a sense of which are the problems that need to be

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:19.440
[Amit Varma]: solved. And today we don't even have an adequate idea of that. So we have blunt tools for blunt

00:43:19.440 --> 00:43:23.720
[Amit Varma]: problems and they might not achieve anything. The other strand I want to take up from what

00:43:23.720 --> 00:43:26.920
[Amit Varma]: you said before was when you spoke about the necessity.

00:43:26.920 --> 00:43:34.400
[Guest]: If I may just stay on that data subject, there is a lot of well-meaning philanthropy in India

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:43.400
[Guest]: where people try to do well. And the answer is that let me go build a free hospital or

00:43:43.400 --> 00:43:52.120
[Guest]: let me go to underserved places like Bihar and run programs to do nutrition interventions

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:59.440
[Guest]: or vaccinations for kids. And I'll try to make kids in Bihar healthier. And in my opinion,

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:06.080
[Guest]: while these things mean well, they don't solve the problem. So the system is broken. And

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:14.080
[Guest]: the highest bang for the buck is in understanding the system, in building knowledge, and in

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:20.640
[Guest]: that long journey of the deeper transformation that is required. So I've seen lots of well-meaning

00:44:20.640 --> 00:44:29.320
[Guest]: people put resourcing into these things and frankly just generate, work on the epiphenomena,

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:34.600
[Guest]: which it just feels good. So there is an instinctive and emotional thing that, oh, there's a person

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:38.840
[Guest]: who's feeling bad or there are so many million children dying in Uttar Pradesh and I want

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:44.320
[Guest]: to make a dent to the number of kids who are dying in Uttar Pradesh. I feel that it would

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:50.040
[Guest]: be more effective to be cold and to be intellectual and to build knowledge and to build a research

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:53.760
[Guest]: community because that's where we will get the deeper solutions and we will stop this

00:44:53.760 --> 00:44:57.560
[Guest]: thing for life. Otherwise, there's a boat that's leaking and you're just bailing and

00:44:57.560 --> 00:45:01.560
[Guest]: you're bailing and we're just not bailing enough to make a material difference. And

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:06.200
[Guest]: year after year, the Indian health system is getting more and more locked into horrible

00:45:06.200 --> 00:45:12.120
[Guest]: incentives and don't underestimate the political economy problems of the incentives because

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:19.360
[Guest]: the malfunctioning heart surgeons of India have all the politicians of India on their

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:24.720
[Guest]: little black books. So they're an extremely effective lobby and when the country changes

00:45:24.720 --> 00:45:30.280
[Guest]: in ways that question their privileges and income, they're going to lobby to change things

00:45:30.280 --> 00:45:35.400
[Guest]: in their way. So every year that we go down this route of bad incentives, we actually

00:45:35.400 --> 00:45:42.880
[Guest]: make things worse. So I feel that we really need to think more effectively in the world

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:50.440
[Guest]: of the well-meaning, generous, philanthropic people who are trying to put resourcing into

00:45:50.440 --> 00:45:58.900
[Guest]: solving this problem. They need to step away from the instant rush of happiness that comes

00:45:58.900 --> 00:46:04.760
[Guest]: from feeding one child to the more abstract conception of building knowledge and building

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:09.440
[Guest]: a research community and building greater thinking capabilities in this country because

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:13.560
[Guest]: in the end, that's the only way we're ever going to solve things. So let me for a moment,

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:17.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, leave the previous strand and I'll come back to that strand later before we pursue

00:46:17.280 --> 00:46:21.000
[Amit Varma]: other strands, but take up this trend. And in this trend, let's move away from the abstract

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:25.400
[Amit Varma]: to the concrete. Let's say that a philanthropist comes to you tomorrow, maybe after listening

00:46:25.400 --> 00:46:30.240
[Amit Varma]: to this episode and says that, oh, you know, I heard you in that episode and I want to

00:46:30.240 --> 00:46:35.200
[Amit Varma]: give you $100 million to spend on health care as you will. And I was going to build hospitals

00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:38.760
[Amit Varma]: in Bihar, but I have realized that that is giving a hungry man a fish. I want to teach

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:44.240
[Amit Varma]: him to fish. I mean, broadly, I just want to make the system work much better. So you,

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:49.320
[Amit Varma]: Ajay Shah, take my $100 million and spend it on improving health care in India. I don't

00:46:49.320 --> 00:46:54.120
[Amit Varma]: care if you're playing the long game, have a 20 year span by all means, but use your

00:46:54.120 --> 00:46:57.320
[Amit Varma]: wisdom and spend it. What are you doing with that $100 million?

00:46:57.320 --> 00:46:59.320
[Guest]: All the things that I said from the beginning.

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:03.760
[Guest]: You said abstract things. Give me a few concrete things. I'll set up this, I'll set up that.

00:47:03.760 --> 00:47:08.800
[Guest]: Build datasets, build research, build researchers, build community, build health policy thinking,

00:47:08.800 --> 00:47:12.520
[Guest]: build health policy debate. One of the tragedies of this country is that we tend to assume

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:16.960
[Guest]: that a doctor thinks health policy. This is completely incorrect. A doctor knows how to

00:47:16.960 --> 00:47:22.040
[Guest]: cut open my chest and perform surgery upon my heart, does not know how to think about

00:47:22.040 --> 00:47:29.280
[Guest]: incentives, markets and systems. So we need to go down the route of building knowledge,

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:36.760
[Guest]: building research, building researchers, and also on some of the science and business models

00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:46.400
[Guest]: around some of the innovations about telemedicine and AI and basically a nurse assisted system

00:47:46.400 --> 00:47:50.480
[Guest]: which would be able to operate in remote places of India because we're not going to have enough

00:47:50.480 --> 00:47:56.120
[Guest]: doctors for the foreseeable future. So this would be my thought process on the big problems

00:47:56.120 --> 00:47:57.280
[Guest]: that require solving.

00:47:57.280 --> 00:48:00.760
[Amit Varma]: So now to come back to my earlier strand where we were speaking about how if you have enough

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:05.000
[Amit Varma]: data entrepreneurs kind of know what holes in the market to fill or what problems to

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:11.960
[Amit Varma]: solve. And you also mentioned the necessity of having sophisticated buyers who understand

00:48:11.960 --> 00:48:15.640
[Amit Varma]: what they're buying into and some of the symmetry of information goes. Now one way of doing

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:20.600
[Amit Varma]: this, as you said, is insurance companies, but there the incentives are also going in

00:48:20.600 --> 00:48:24.720
[Amit Varma]: another direction and I don't know how that works out. And it strikes me that this is

00:48:24.720 --> 00:48:30.920
[Amit Varma]: also a great market opportunity that entrepreneurs can look at this lack of sophisticated buyers

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:35.920
[Amit Varma]: or the lack that every individual would feel of a sophisticated buyer within herself and

00:48:35.920 --> 00:48:40.280
[Amit Varma]: say that, okay, how do I kind of fill this gap? Do you think there's a gap like that?

00:48:40.280 --> 00:48:44.040
[Amit Varma]: And what role do you think AI can have in filling that gap? Like one of the things that

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:47.920
[Amit Varma]: we've seen during COVID, one of the great tragedies, in fact, I mean, it's just so sad

00:48:47.920 --> 00:48:52.440
[Amit Varma]: when the Twitter timeline is full of calls for plasma and remdesivir and we know that

00:48:52.440 --> 00:48:58.600
[Amit Varma]: plasma does not work. And remdesivir basically does not work in the context of delaying fatalities

00:48:58.600 --> 00:49:03.600
[Amit Varma]: or in serious cases at all. It's just a waste of time. And yet, you know, patients will

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:08.160
[Amit Varma]: go to doctors and say, Oh, what about plasma? What about remdesivir? Doctors will, you know,

00:49:08.160 --> 00:49:12.680
[Amit Varma]: just go by the form and as I'm okay, fine, you know, to get the patients off their back.

00:49:12.680 --> 00:49:17.480
[Amit Varma]: I've actually heard of people, relatives of patients contracting COVID because they've

00:49:17.480 --> 00:49:21.920
[Amit Varma]: been running all around the city trying to get plasma and remdesivir. And this just seems

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:27.400
[Amit Varma]: so completely ridiculous. And you can't blame them because in that moment, in that chaos

00:49:27.400 --> 00:49:31.840
[Amit Varma]: of emotion in the middle of Armageddon, as it were, when you could have an aged parent

00:49:31.840 --> 00:49:36.040
[Amit Varma]: on oxygen and the doctors telling you get this, get that, in that moment, you can't

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:41.440
[Amit Varma]: expect sophistication. Is there a way where outside the current system, there is a disruptive

00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:45.640
[Amit Varma]: way of coming in and solving for this problem? Maybe in the long run, you know, AI could

00:49:45.640 --> 00:49:49.440
[Amit Varma]: be part of the puzzle. But you know, what are your thoughts?

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:57.280
[Guest]: So bottleneck is scale. Okay, so the entire Indian healthcare landscape is broken, particularly

00:49:57.280 --> 00:50:05.400
[Guest]: in North India. Okay, so I want to use a word, which will set off alarm bells in the minds

00:50:05.400 --> 00:50:10.440
[Guest]: of many people, but I want to use the word corruption. So when a doctor distorts her

00:50:10.440 --> 00:50:17.960
[Guest]: professional judgment in return for some kickbacks, I call that corruption. And the entire business

00:50:17.960 --> 00:50:24.840
[Guest]: model of individuals and organizations is rooted around these corrupt practices. It's

00:50:24.840 --> 00:50:30.000
[Guest]: not easy for any one organization to change that. So imagine, you and I are going to set

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:35.280
[Guest]: up a brand new hospital, and we will have a different wage structure for the doctors

00:50:35.280 --> 00:50:41.800
[Guest]: that we might hire. And we will say to the doctors, no kickbacks. Okay, and the quick

00:50:41.800 --> 00:50:47.720
[Guest]: outcome will be no sensible profit maximizing doctor will want to join us. How do you overcome

00:50:47.720 --> 00:50:52.320
[Guest]: that? Christian Medical College, well, it has solved that problem. Because they have

00:50:52.320 --> 00:50:59.400
[Guest]: created an amazing history, a culture, a tradition. And they've managed to say this to a large

00:50:59.400 --> 00:51:04.320
[Guest]: number of early stage doctors in their careers that look, if you have these kind of values,

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:09.720
[Guest]: come back and be with us. And that's how they have overcome the problem. But there is no

00:51:09.720 --> 00:51:13.760
[Guest]: ready business model through which you can overcome this problem. By the way, we've seen

00:51:13.760 --> 00:51:18.440
[Guest]: this exact same problem in finance. Okay, so in finance, we have that same pervasive

00:51:18.440 --> 00:51:24.040
[Guest]: problem. Naciket Moore and Bindu Anand and others built a remarkable organization that

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:32.600
[Guest]: is called KGFS. Today, KGFS is significantly profitable. And they began going to remote

00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:36.720
[Guest]: locations where there was not even a bank branch and performing basic financial services

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:41.000
[Guest]: for poor people. Okay, and it was great, more power to them. The trouble is, if you try

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:46.160
[Guest]: bringing that model to a city, and in the city, you're competing against hard driving

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:52.000
[Guest]: finance distributors, and finance salespeople who are being given kickbacks, how do you

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:56.280
[Guest]: compete with that and an organization where employees get salaries and employees don't

00:51:56.280 --> 00:52:04.360
[Guest]: get kickbacks will not easily be able to compete against the kickback model until a lot goes

00:52:04.360 --> 00:52:09.760
[Guest]: in in terms of getting the message to households that you really should not be dealing with

00:52:09.760 --> 00:52:17.080
[Guest]: these toxic characters. Okay, so I used to do innumerable talks in finance, and I used

00:52:17.080 --> 00:52:22.920
[Guest]: to always try to put in a public service announcement that please don't ever buy an insurance product

00:52:22.920 --> 00:52:28.380
[Guest]: in India, because the entire business model of insurance is broken. And it took years

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:33.800
[Guest]: and years and years of that. But there have been significant improvements in the business

00:52:33.800 --> 00:52:38.760
[Guest]: model of insurance companies, which were driven by the IRDA was driven by the state. So if

00:52:38.760 --> 00:52:45.160
[Guest]: I make that analogy here, then we are up against a long slow battle that we'd need to build

00:52:45.160 --> 00:52:51.280
[Guest]: some amount of, you know, medical malpractice law and tort law, and consumer protection

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:58.920
[Guest]: law and regulation of the behavior of medical persons. And the moment I say all this stuff,

00:52:58.920 --> 00:53:04.200
[Guest]: I already start getting depressed. Because it is incredibly difficult to build this kind

00:53:04.200 --> 00:53:08.800
[Guest]: of state capacity under Indian conditions. And in fact, we have failed in so many other

00:53:08.800 --> 00:53:14.000
[Guest]: areas, that I don't think it's wise to recommend that toolkit for one more new area, it seems

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:18.600
[Guest]: to me we should fix it in the other areas. This is broken in all the other areas where

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:23.400
[Guest]: it's up and running. So, you know, I feel that the cutting edge, what one would say

00:53:23.400 --> 00:53:29.520
[Guest]: to the philanthropist, the cutting edge of health policy is to make SEBI work better.

00:53:29.520 --> 00:53:33.280
[Guest]: Because if one day we get to a SEBI that works, we'll be able to take elements of that law

00:53:33.280 --> 00:53:35.920
[Guest]: and organization design and apply that to health.

00:53:35.920 --> 00:53:40.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, that makes sense that, you know, given state capacity, we haven't managed to

00:53:40.760 --> 00:53:47.160
[Amit Varma]: get ABC right, we can hardly speak of XYZ or even Shakespeare's plays.

00:53:47.160 --> 00:53:52.960
[Guest]: And, you know, I'm very mindful of the word state coercion. So much as I like to complain

00:53:52.960 --> 00:53:56.960
[Guest]: about kickbacks and corruption, the fact is, when you bring a coercive creature called

00:53:56.960 --> 00:54:03.000
[Guest]: the state that has pretty bad consequences of its own. So we should think 20 times before

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:07.700
[Guest]: we bring state violence into the relationship between a doctor and a patient. It has its

00:54:07.700 --> 00:54:12.440
[Guest]: own bad consequences, it will have its own malfunction. So let's not be starry eyed

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:17.120
[Guest]: about what state intervention would do. So we're caught between these two bad worlds.

00:54:17.120 --> 00:54:23.200
[Guest]: And our pathway for the coming years is to build knowledge, is to build research, is

00:54:23.200 --> 00:54:27.680
[Guest]: to build researchers, is to build data sets, is to build a health policy community, which

00:54:27.680 --> 00:54:30.880
[Guest]: is distinct and separate from doctors.

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:36.280
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful. So, you know, we could really do a four, five, eight, 10 hour episode on talking

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:41.120
[Amit Varma]: about healthcare. But I guess the urgent sort of imperative of the moment is to talk more

00:54:41.120 --> 00:54:45.560
[Amit Varma]: about the economics and politics of vaccination. And, you know, what's happening with that

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:49.560
[Amit Varma]: in this current moment. But let's let's take a quick commercial break. And then on the

